/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1245:- `BMO^{-1}` is the weakest candidate in this menu for a compactness-rigidity program. It is excellent for small-data mild theory, but it is a poor default host for a large-data minimal blowup extraction unless one can point to a concrete nonlinear profile decomposition and a robust stability theory in exactly that setting.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1247:So the step's framing is too loose. "Rank realistic spaces" sounds harmless, but the real burden is to prove that at least one space supports the whole package: local theory, perturbation theory, profile decomposition, symmetry normalization, pressure control, and a notion of compactness compatible with the intended rigidity lever. A ranking memo can hide the fact that no candidate actually clears that bar.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1249:The kill condition is also weakly calibrated. "No candidate space supports a credible minimal-element package" is correct in spirit, but "credible" invites hand-waving. The branch should die unless one can name the exact extraction theorem, stability theorem, and compactness notion to be used, not just a favored space.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1259:There is also a sequencing problem. In most compactness-rigidity programs, the hypothetical critical element tells you what rigidity information is even geometrically available. Here the chain asks for the rigidity weapon before it knows the target's regularity, compactness modulus, or pressure information. That is backwards.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1268:- "State exactly what compactness or almost-periodicity statements are required" is really asking for the core theorem. If those statements are missing, the program is not partially built; it is blocked at the foundation.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1279:- In NS there is no standard virial, channel of energy, or finite-speed mechanism waiting to be plugged in once compactness appears.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1281:- The pressure term is a recurring spoiler. Any rigidity mechanism that depends on second-order pressure structure can fail simply because the available compactness is too weak to pass that structure to the limit.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1283:The "first missing NS-specific lemma" criterion is good in spirit but under-specified. Many such lemmas are just the regularity problem in disguise. The chain should require a real complexity drop: the missing lemma should apply to a much narrower class than arbitrary finite-energy solutions and should exploit the compactness normalization in an essential way.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1285:The downgrade rule is also too binary. A lever can fail without collapsing to Tao-preserved structure. It can fail because the compactness class is too weak, because the quantity is not coercive, or because the limiting object lacks the regularity needed to state the argument. Those are different failure modes and should be separated.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1291:- A "compactness-plus-rigidity roadmap" is too cheap an output after four steps. The chain can still exit with an elegant narrative that hides the absence of any executable theorem path.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1295:The kill condition only guards against rhetorical blur across multiple phase spaces or levers. It does not guard against the more likely failure: smuggling in an unproved stability theorem or an unearned compactness statement while pretending the only remaining gap is the sexy NS-specific rigidity lemma.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1299:- The whole chain is structurally biased toward a predetermined conclusion: if local estimates stall, pivot to concentration-compactness plus rigidity. That is a familiar aesthetic move, not an argued reason that this is the best remaining path.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1327:missions/beyond-de-giorgi/library-inbox/step-007-exploration-001-l3-host-space-audit.md:73:| local theory | `[VERIFIED]` The local record names `L^3` as a serious critical candidate, and `ckn-1982-proof-architecture.md` confirms that `L^3` is the scale-invariant velocity quantity appearing in the classical suitable-weak framework through `C(r) = r^{-2} \iint |u|^3`. `[INFERRED]` That is not the same as a local well-posedness theorem for an `L^3` host-space compactness program. | `[INFERRED]` The branch either stays with suitable weak / Leray-Hopf plus LEI, or it drifts toward a mild critical-space flow. The local corpus does not freeze one of those. | `[VERIFIED]` `run-004/attacks/chain-02.md` warns that `L^3` sits next to strong endpoint regularity results, so this is already a crowded prior-art zone. | `[VERIFIED]` No local theorem packet gives an `L^3` local theory in the exact Step-1 sense. |
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1329:missions/beyond-de-giorgi/library-inbox/step-007-exploration-001-l3-host-space-audit.md:78:| compactness usable by later rigidity | `[VERIFIED]` `decision-010.md`, `step-007/GOAL.md`, and `run-004/judgments/chain-02.md` all demand a compactness notion usable later, not just a suggestive host space. `[VERIFIED]` `lin-1998-proof-architecture.md` contains contradiction-plus-compactness at the epsilon-regularity scale, but not threshold compactness for a large-data critical element. | `[INFERRED]` The compactness notion would have to survive the chosen solution class, pressure handling, and normalization. | `[VERIFIED]` This is the sharpest overlap with the generic Kenig-Merle template: language is present, theorem packet is not. | `[VERIFIED]` No local source instantiates a usable threshold compactness theorem for `L^3`. |
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/runtime/logs/codex-patlas-beyond-de-giorgi-step-007-curator-002.log:1336:missions/beyond-de-giorgi/CHAIN.md:5:A compactness-rigidity route is live only if one specific critical or near-critical host space supports an explicit extraction package, one theorem-like minimal blowup object, and one rigidity quantity that is actually defined on that class and can drive a contradiction.
