/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:42:### Vasseur (2010) — "Higher derivatives estimate for the 3D Navier-Stokes equation"
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:44:- **Key result:** Estimates on higher derivatives of NS solutions up to potential blow-up time using De Giorgi with Hardy spaces and maximal functions.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:45:- **H^1/Hardy role:** Second derivatives of pressure lie in Hardy H^1 ⊂ L^1 (CLMS). Explicitly acknowledges that the maximal function is not L^1-bounded, forcing a new pressure splitting strategy.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:50:### Choi-Vasseur (2014) — "Estimates on fractional higher derivatives of weak solutions for the Navier-Stokes equations"
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:59:  - **The second derivatives of pressure lie in H^1 via CLMS**, explicitly stated on page 5. The new decomposition is designed specifically to work with H^1 pressure structure despite the non-bounded maximal operator.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:60:- **Exponent achieved:** U_k ≤ C^k · U_{k-1}^{7/6}, which can be made close to 4/3 (Remarks 3.1, 3.6). The scaling-optimal target is 4/3 = 4/(d+1) for d=2, and 7/6 > 1 suffices for convergence. **This does NOT reach 3/2.** The paper is about higher-derivative estimates, not about closing the 4/3 → 3/2 gap.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:67:- **Key result:** Second spatial derivatives of suitable weak solutions are locally in Lorentz space L^{4/3,q} for any q > 4/3, improving the previous L^{4/3,∞} bound of Choi-Vasseur.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:105:- Choi-Vasseur 2014: achieved ~4/3 (specifically 7/6) for fractional derivative estimates — same ceiling
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:106:- Vasseur-Yang 2021: circumvented pressure via vorticity for second-derivative estimates — but didn't close the 4/3 → 3/2 gap for full regularity
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:159:3. **H^1-BMO duality (Step 2B) remains viable as an untried angle.** The Vasseur school has used H^1 structure of the pressure (second derivatives of p are in H^1 via CLMS) but has NOT tested whether the De Giorgi test functions ψ_k are uniformly BMO-bounded. If they are, the H^1-BMO duality pairing replaces Hölder and potentially achieves the 3/2 threshold. This is the genuine novel angle.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:161:4. **Vorticity route (Vasseur-Yang 2021) is an alternative.** By reformulating via ω = curl u (which has no pressure term), the pressure obstruction is avoided. However, this does NOT directly address the full-regularity conjecture (Conjecture 14 of Vasseur 2007) — it achieves second-derivative estimates, not L^∞ bounds.
